                <head>191. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On December 26, the President met at the White House from 9:03 to 9:55 a.m. with
                    Director of Central Intelligence <persName corresp="#p_DAW1">Allen
                        Dulles</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_EMJSD1">John S.D.
                        Eisenhower</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_GBGAJ1">Andrew
                        Goodpaster</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_GG1">Gordon
                    Gray</persName>. (Eisenhower Library, President’s Daily Appointments) According
                    to a memorandum of the conference prepared by <persName corresp="#p_GGO1"
                        >Gray</persName> on December 30, the President “expressed a feeling that for
                    one reason or another the main elements of the Cuban situation had not been
                    presented to him.” <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> said he
                    planned to speak with Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">Dulles</persName>
                    “about better coordination.” The President also indicated that “he did not wish
                    the specifics of covert operations to be presented to the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>.” (Eisenhower Library, Project “Clean-Up”
                    Records, Meetings with the President) The memorandum is published in <hi
                        rend="italic">Declassified Documents, 1983</hi>, 1342.</p>
            </div>
